text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!English vs. Zulu (Clicks)%0a%0a:Author: aarnavp%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aUncommon Consonants: English and Zulu%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aAccording to WALS, there are 4 classes of uncommon consonants employed by languages, the rarest being clicks – an obstruent sound formed from two closures in front and back of mouth, which then releases air through front of mouth (ingressive airstream mechanism). Clicks are mainly used in southeast African languages, a prominent one being Zulu of South Africa from the Bantoid language family. While English may use clicks for "non-linguistic communication" (e.g "tsk tsk"), Zulu is a language that encodes meaning with its 4 click consonants.%0a%0a%0aWhile English has no clicks present in their consonant inventory, Zulu uses three glottal ingressive clicks – the post-alveoalar kǃ, dental k|, and alveolar lateral k|| clicks [PHOIBLE]. %0a%0aIt's interesting to note that clicks are known for its reflection of geographical linguistic distribution, as clicks are mainly concentrated in southeastern/eastern African languages, stemming from Khoisan language families. While most languages may contain different consonants, I didn't realize it would differ in airstream mechanisms too. It's interesting to think about what condition led to the proliferation of the ingressive air stream in these languages that wasn't present in English. %0a%0aWALS: https://wals.info/chapter/19%0aPHOIBLE: https://phoible.org/inventories/view/147%0aWikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Click_consonant%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 221005-212902-640060#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Expansion to English vs. Zulu (Clicks) %0a-> - maxwell%0a-> [-05.10.2022 - 14:29-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221005-212902-640060 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI came across this article comparing the roles of clicks in English vs Zulu: https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/just-a-click-away/%0aOne thing it mentions is how linguistic and genetic data has led some researchers to argue that the language spoken by humans prior to our movement out of Africa made use of click consonants. However, the article also cites research showing that while clicks faded away as consonants in languages outside of Africa, they can still play important roles in communication. Based on large sets of recorded British and American English conversations, the researcher Melissa Wright found that clicks are often used to signal a transition from one topic to another – comparable to the role of “anyway” or “so.” Based on this, the article concludes that what really happened was more nuanced than clicks simply fading out of use – rather, they have taken on different but still important roles in other languages.%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221005-212902-640060#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: D:)%0a(:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)%0a(:Title: English vs. Zulu (Clicks):)
