diff:1665005342:1664492031:=57,73c57%0a%3c #foxbegin 221005-212902-640060#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Expansion to English vs. Zulu (Clicks) %0a%3c -> - maxwell%0a%3c -> [-05.10.2022 - 14:29-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221005-212902-640060 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c I came across this article comparing the roles of clicks in English vs Zulu: https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/just-a-click-away/%0a%3c One thing it mentions is how linguistic and genetic data has led some researchers to argue that the language spoken by humans prior to our movement out of Africa made use of click consonants. However, the article also cites research showing that while clicks faded away as consonants in languages outside of Africa, they can still play important roles in communication. Based on large sets of recorded British and American English conversations, the researcher Melissa Wright found that clicks are often used to signal a transition from one topic to another – comparable to the role of “anyway” or “so.” Based on this, the article concludes that what really happened was more nuanced than clicks simply fading out of use – rather, they have taken on different but still important roles in other languages.%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221005-212902-640060#%0a---%0a> %0a
